snippet.textDisplay: Tom, this is absolutely incredible. I thought I loved your music before, but this has set a whole new level for that. I've always been a fan of your decision to write and give a spotlight to subject matter that too many people are afraid to address. While this is a lot less controversial than other pieces of your work, this song has to be my favorite now. While I've not personally struggled with addiction to a substance, I know many people who have, some who have been very close to me. I didn't struggle with that same kind of addiction, but I've spent many years battling my own demons in the mental health department. While this song is not directly related to my own struggles, I feel like the chorus still speaks to me very strongly, and for that, I thank you.

snippet.textDisplay: Currently dating a someone whos also recovering from shit. Knowing her past and all the hell shes gone through.. Seeing her progress and being there to help support her in times when shes wanted to relapse, never went to a rehab or used any govt drugs to get off the shit, Im damn proud of her. She hit a very deep hole in her life and thats pretty much where I found her but something about her drew me in. We just passed 4 months together, wanting and starting to build a life together because whatever sort of bond appeared we needed, and neither of us could be happier. I dont plan on leaving her side, she doesnt plan on leaving mine. Its possible to get off stuff and rebuild. As she states it, "You have to want it enough."

snippet.textDisplay: on day 6 of heroin withdrawal. still can’t sleep through the night, took like 5 baths to try and calm my restless body but couldn’t find anything to calm my restless mind. scrolled through my YouTube recommendations and my higher power placed this song here for me to listen to on repeat to remind me that the battle is never over but it’s possible to get through, it gets better and im not alone. don’t ever cry like I need to but this shit brought me to tears. i needed this. thank you.

snippet.textDisplay: i’ve had so many vices in my life that hindered me from becoming who i truly am. i smoked weed everyday, drank, partied whenever it was possible, everything you can imagine aside from shooting up. then battled a opiate addiction for about 7 years. worst years of my life. but i’m glad to say as of jan 18th 2020, i’ve been clean 100% for 11 years. now i’m the man i needed to be all those years. it’s never to late to change and get help. it’s going to be hard, really hard. but those demons CAN BE DEFEATED! i wish you all the best. god bless
